## Latency & Throughput Metrics: Summary Table

This table provides a breakdown of common latency and throughput metrics, their definitions, units, and typical ranges.‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀIt's designed to help you understand the key performance indicators (KPIs) used to assess system performance in various contexts.

| **Metric** | **Definition** | **Units** | **Typical Range** | **Importance/Use Case** |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Latency** | The time it takes for a request to be processed and a response to be received.‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀIt's the delay experienced by the user or system. | Milliseconds (ms), Seconds (s) |‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀ< 10ms (very good), 10-100ms (acceptable), 100-500ms (can be problematic), > 500ms (poor)| **Critical for user experience, responsiveness, and real-time applications.** Measures how quickly a user can complete tasks. |
| **Throughput** | The amount of data processed or operations completed within a given time period. It's the rate at which a system is working. | Transactions per second (TPS), Requests per second (RPS), Data transferred per second (bps)‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀ| < 10 TPS, 10-100 TPS, 100-1000 TPS, > 1000 TPS | **Measures the system's capacity and scalability.** Indicates how much work can be handled. Important for assessing resource needs and planning infrastructure. |
| **Request Response Time** |‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀSpecifically measures the time taken to process a request from start to finish. Often closely related to latency but includes any processing delays within the request handling pipeline. | Milliseconds (ms), Seconds (s) | < 20ms, 20-100ms, 100-500ms |‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀSimilar to Latency - crucial for user experience and application responsiveness.|
| **CPU Utilization** | The percentage of time the CPU is busy processing tasks. | Percentage (%) | < 70%, 70-90%, 90-100% (high) | **Indicates system load and potential bottlenecks.**‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀHigh CPU utilization can signal resource constraints or inefficient code.|
| **Memory Utilization** | The amount of RAM being used by the system. | Percentage (%) | < 80%, 80-90%, 90-100% (high) | **Indicates memory pressure and potential swapping.**‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀHigh memory usage can lead to performance degradation and crashes.|
| **Disk I/O (Input/Output)** | The rate at which data is being read from or written to the disk. | Transactions per second (TPS), Bytes per second (bps) | < 10 TPS, 10-50 TPS, 50-200 TPS, > 200 TPS| **Measures storage performance.** Slow disk I/O can significantly impact application performance.|
| **Network Latency** | The delay in data transmission over a network.‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀOften measured between servers or devices. | Milliseconds (ms) | < 1ms, 1-5ms, 5-10ms, > 10ms (high) | **Critical for distributed systems and real-time communication.** Impacts the responsiveness of networked applications.|
| **Network Throughput** | The amount of data successfully transmitted over a network within a given time period.‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀMeasured in bits per second (bps) or bytes per second (Bps). | Bits per second (bps), Bytes per second (Bps) | < 1 Mbps, 1-5 Mbps, 5-10 Mbps, > 10 Mbps| **Measures network bandwidth and data transfer rate.**‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀImportant for assessing the capacity of network connections.|
| **Error Rate** | The percentage of requests that result in errors. | Percentage (%) | < 1%, 1-5%, 5-10% (high) | **Indicates system stability and reliability.** High error rates can lead to data loss and application downtime.|
| **Connection Time** |‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀThe time it takes to establish a network connection (e.g., TCP handshake). | Milliseconds (ms) | < 10ms, 10-50ms, 50-200ms (high)|‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀImportant for applications requiring quick connections and efficient resource allocation.|

**Key Considerations:**

* **Context Matters:** The "typical range" for each metric depends heavily on the application's requirements. A web server handling many concurrent requests will have different ranges than a single-threaded process.
* **Correlation is Important:**‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀIt‚Äôs crucial to correlate these metrics to understand the root cause of performance issues. For example, high CPU utilization coupled with slow disk I/O might indicate that the application is overloaded with data.
* **Monitoring Tools:** Use appropriate monitoring tools (e.g., Prometheus, Grafana, Datadog, New Relic) to collect and analyze these metrics in real-time.
* **Baseline & Trends:** Establish a baseline for each metric under normal operating conditions, and monitor trends over time to identify potential issues early on.


This table is a starting point; adapt it based on the specific needs of your application and infrastructure.‚ĖĀ‚ĖĀRemember to prioritize the metrics that are most critical for your business objectives.




